            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="div-container-code">
            <div class="w-embed">
              <video id="myVideo" muted autoplay playsinline>
                <source src="/alex-perez-uGXEEwnvIkQ-unsplash-vsnonprogressive-h265.mp4" type="video/mp4; codecs=hvc1" />
                <source src="/alex-perez-uGXEEwnvIkQ-unsplash-vsnonprogressive-h264.mp4" type="video/mp4; codecs=mp4v" />
                <source src="/alex-perez-uGXEEwnvIkQ-unsplash-vsnonprogressive-VP9.webm" type="video/webm; codecs=vp9" />
                <source src="/alex-perez-uGXEEwnvIkQ-unsplash-vsnonprogressive-h264.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
              </video>

              <script is:inline>
                const video = document.getElementById('myVideo');
                if (video) {
                  video.addEventListener('ended', function () {
                    setTimeout(() => {
                      video.currentTime = 0;
                      video.play();
                    }, 2000);
                  });
                }
              </script>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="size-60px"></div>
          <div class="wrapper-text centered width-rem">
            <p class="text-xl-light is-centered">
              With JPEG&nbsp;XL’s state-of-the-art progressive encoding and decoding, you’ll see an image sooner than with other formats &mdash; with as little as 1% of the image loaded. It supports both saliency progression (visually important areas of the image delivered first) and reordering (middle data sent first).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="size-xxhuge-12rem-192px"></div>
      </section>

